---
description: Keep scan, task_process, and serial_store responsibilities separated
alwaysApply: true
---

# Fetch Branch Persistence Boundaries

When working on branch persistence in `fetch/`:

- `scan/flow.go` owns branch materialization from `BlockTree`. It may convert leaf-first branches into low-to-high payloads and backfill missing body tasks on the fetch side before handing branches off.
- `task_process/` owns header/full-block fetch and staging updates. If header insertion should trigger body work, do it from `task_process` or another fetch-side coordinator, not from `serial_store`.
- `serial_store/` owns only serialized branch traversal and DB persistence. It must not depend directly on `taskpool`, enqueue fetch work, or define task orchestration callbacks.

Preferred direction:

- Put fetch scheduling and retry triggers in `scan`, `task_process`, or runtime wiring that already owns task orchestration.
- Keep `serial_store` focused on parent-readiness checks, ordered persistence, and branch-local stop conditions.

Examples:

- Bad: add `SetBodyTaskEnqueuer(...)` or any task-pool callback to `fetch/serial_store/Worker`.
- Bad: move missing-body task scheduling into `serial_store`.
- Good: let `scan` submit low-to-high branches to `serial_store`.
- Good: let `task_process` enqueue body work when newly inserted headers should trigger fetch.
